<kml>

<concept name=Harm><system-documentation name=Harm>
<superconcept name=Impair>

<definition>
  Harm an object that is a living thing so it becomes weakened. The object 
  can still perform its function, but at a diminished capacity.
</definition>

<requiredslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=object>
     The object that's harmed. The object is a living thing.
  </slotdescription>

</requiredslotlist>

<primaryslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=agent>
    the entity that caused the harm to occur.
  </slotdescription>

  <slotdescription name=instrument>
    the thing that was used to harm the object.
  </slotdescription>

  <slotdescription name=by-means-of>
    the event that caused the harm to occur.
  </slotdescription>

</primaryslotlist>

<examplesentencelist>

  <examplesentence>
    <text>The man harmed the dog by neglecting the dog.</text>
    <slotdescription name=agent>the Man</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=object>the Dog</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=by-means-of>Neglect</slotdescription>
  </examplesentence>
  <comment>
     The dog is a living thing that becomes weakened or diminished.
  </comment>

</examplesentencelist>

<neighborlist>

  <neighbor name=Impair>
     An impair is a general kind of harm where the object does not
     have to be a living thing.
  </neighbor>

  <neighbor name=Damage>
     A damage is similar to a harm, but the object being damaged is
     not a living thing.
  </neighbor>

</neighborlist>

</kml>


